  1. Use map function to show the mode (most frequent category) and the number of categories for each categorical variables. Put the result in data frame.
getmode <- function(x) {
  levels <- na.omit(unique(x))
  tab <- tabulate(match(x, levels))
  levels[tab == max(tab)][1]
}
df<- titanic %>%
  select_if(is.character)%>%
  select(-c(Name))

map_df(df, function(x){c(getmode(x),
                         nlevels(factor(x)))
  })

  1. Redo Question 11 in Assignment 7 using map. Hint: You may want to use a nested map. For instance this following codes print out all the possibility of x+y where both x and y are running from 1 to 2.

"Write a function for a quick visualization that input a (cleaned) data and a number \(k\) and output the follows

  • If \(k=1\), output all the possible bar charts of a categorical variable filled by another categorical variables where both of the two variables must have the number of categories less than 4.
  • If \(k=2\), output all the possible density curve (using geom_density), i.e.density curves of all numeric variables
  • If \(k=3\), all possible density curves of all numeric variables coloring by a categorical variable with the number of categories less than 4."
six<-function(z,k){
  validcols <- titanic[, sapply(titanic, function(col) length(unique(col))) < 4]
  numericCols<-titanic%>%
    select_if(is.numeric)
  
  if (k==1){map(validcols, function(x){map(validcols, function(y){ggplot(validcols, aes(factor(x), fill=factor(y)))+geom_bar()})})}
  else if (k==2){map(numericCols, function(x){ggplot(numericCols, aes(x))+geom_density()})}
  else if (k==3){map(numericCols, function(x){map(validcols, function(y){ggplot(titanic, aes(x, color=factor(y)))+geom_density()})})}
  else {print("Error")}
}
six(titanic, 1)

  1. Write a function, using map, to

input: a data frame output: a data frame of consist three columns x1, x2 and r where the pairs (x1,x2) are all possible pairs of continuous variables of the input data frame and r is the corresponding r square of x1 and x2. Test the function on the titanic data assuming that the PassengerID is also a coninuous variable.

lm_loop<-function(input){
  frame<-input%>%select_if(is.numeric)
  t<-names(frame)
  map_df(frame, function(y) {map(frame, ~summary(lm(y ~.x, data=frame))$r.squared) })%>%
    mutate(y=t) %>%
    gather(x, value="r.squared", -y)%>%
    select(x, everything())}
output<-lm_loop(titanic)
